Let AnCoGen Encode the Residual of Speech

Author

Samir Sadok

\(\small \text{This paper aims to establish a methodology and present internal experimental results.}\)

Introduction

Masked modeling is a self-supervised learning technique in which parts of the input are masked, and the model predicts the missing elements from context, enhancing representation learning and robustness. Popular examples of such techniques are BERT (Sadok et al. 2025), a model trained to reconstruct parts of sentences, and the Masked Autoencoder (MAE) (He et al. 2022), a model trained to reconstruct missing image patches from the visible ones. More precisely, in the original MAE (He et al. 2022), an input image is split into non-overlapping patches projected into embedding vectors and randomly masked. Only the visible (non-masked) embeddings are processed by the encoder. The masked embeddings (not processed by the encoder) are replaced with a , and the complete sequence of encoded embeddings and mask tokens is given to the decoder for reconstruction. This simple strategy forces the encoder to produce representations that can be used to reconstruct the content in the missing tokens, thus embedding enough contextual information to that aim.

The masked autoencoder learning paradigm has also proven successful in other data types, such as audio signals of speech. Indeed, AnCoGen (Sadok et al. 2025) relies on masked modeling to learn a bidirectional relationship between a Mel spectrogram (low-level representation close to the raw signal) and high-level attributes including linguistic, prosodic, and acoustic features. This approach maps Mel-spectrogram tokens to speech attributes (analysis) and reverses the process of mapping attributes back to Mel-spectrogram tokens (generation). The attribute-based representation allows for easier and more intuitive modification (control) of the speech signal.

Question

Can the residual information be effectively encoded in a latent space? That is, can we capture and represent the additional attributes not explicitly provided as inputs to the AnCoGen model?

Intuition

By using a latent space as in the Perceiver architecture, we aim to capture and represent the additional attributes that are not explicitly provided as inputs to the AnCoGen model. This latent space serves as a compact, trainable representation that can selectively attend to the input data and encode the missing or implicit information necessary for the task.

Methdodology

In speech modeling, the input is often factorized into well-defined components or factors or attributes such as content (phonetic or linguistic information), speaker embedding (identity-related features), pitch, and loudness. However, these attributes do not fully account for the richness and variability present in natural speech. We refer to the residual information as the set of characteristics that remain unaccounted for by these explicit factors. This includes, but is not limited to:

  • Speaking style (e.g., formal vs. casual, fast vs. slow);
  • Emotion and affective state;
  • Articulatory nuances or accents;
  • Expressive timing and micro-prosody;
  • Coarticulation effects and non-verbal vocalizations (e.g., breaths, sighs).
How ?

Capturing this residual information is crucial for generating expressive and natural speech. Since these features are often subtle, entangled, and difficult to annotate explicitly, we propose to learn them implicitly using a latent space. This latent representation is expected to encode the remaining degrees of freedom in the speech signal that are not covered by the provided attributes.

The problem with AnCoGen (Sadok et al. 2025) model is that it fails to represent this residual information — the implicit, underlying factors that contribute to the expressiveness and naturalness of speech. To address this, we propose the introduction of a latent space in the AnCoGen model. This latent space will allow the model to learn and represent the residual information that is not explicitly included in the input attributes.

Latent Space: From Perceiver to AnCoGen

The concept of a latent space is central to the Perceiver architecture, where it enables scalable and flexible processing of high-dimensional and multimodal data. Rather than applying self-attention directly to large or variable-sized inputs, Perceiver introduces a fixed-size set of latent vectors that are learned during training. These latent vectors do not directly encode the input; instead, they attend to the input features through a cross-attention mechanism, where each latent vector queries the entire input space and aggregates information based on its learned attention weights. This allows the model to selectively extract and compress relevant information from potentially massive input data into a compact latent representation. Once this interaction is complete, the latents are refined through several layers of self-attention and feedforward processing, all performed within the fixed latent space. This architectural design decouples the computational cost from the input size and makes the Perceiver highly adaptable to a wide range of modalities, including vision, audio, and language.

In this setup, the latent vectors act as the queries (\(Q\)), while the input data (e.g.embeddings) provide the keys (\(K\)) and values (\(V\)). For each latent vector, attention weights are computed by measuring its similarity (typically via dot product) to each input key. These weights are then used to compute a weighted sum over the values, producing an updated latent that selectively integrates relevant information from the input. This mechanism allows each latent to focus on different aspects of the input, effectively compressing the entire input into a fixed number of informative latent representations, regardless of the input’s original size.

Cross-Attention in Perceiver

Input: - Input data \(\mathbf{x} \in \mathbb{R}^{N \times D_{\text{in}}}\) - Latent vectors \(\mathbf{z} \in \mathbb{R}^{M \times D_{\text{latent}}}\)

Algorithm:

  1. Project queries: \(\mathbf{Q} \leftarrow \mathbf{z} \mathbf{W}_q\)
  2. Project keys: \(\mathbf{K} \leftarrow \mathbf{x} \mathbf{W}_k\)
  3. Project values: \(\mathbf{V} \leftarrow \mathbf{x} \mathbf{W}_v\)
  4. Compute attention weights:
    \(\mathbf{A} \leftarrow \text{softmax} \left( \frac{\mathbf{Q} \mathbf{K}^\top}{\sqrt{d}} \right)\)
  5. Compute attended representations:
    \(\mathbf{Z}_{\text{attn}} \leftarrow \mathbf{A} \mathbf{V}\)
  6. Add residual and normalize:
    \(\mathbf{Z}_{\text{norm}} \leftarrow \text{LayerNorm}(\mathbf{z} + \mathbf{Z}_{\text{attn}})\)
  7. Final output:
    \(\mathbf{Z}_{\text{out}} \leftarrow \text{FeedForward}(\mathbf{Z}_{\text{norm}})\)

Output: \(\mathbf{Z}_{\text{out}}\)

Inspired by this approach, we propose to incorporate a similar latent space into the AnCoGen model to enhance its flexibility and expressiveness (see Figure 1). While AnCoGen generates speech conditioned on explicit attributes like pitch and timbre, there remains additional, implicit information that is not directly captured—such as speaking style, articulation patterns, prosody, and residual identity traits (see more in Section 2). By introducing a learnable latent space that interacts with the input Mel-spectrogram via cross-attention, we aim to encode this complementary information in a compact, trainable form. This latent space acts as a bottleneck, enabling the model to infer and organize the residual degrees of freedom in the speech signal, ultimately allowing for the generation of richer and more natural speech outputs.

Controlling the information in the latent space

In the AnCoGen model, without any intervention, the latent space will encode all the information necessary to generate the mel-spectrogram, which includes not only the explicit attributes such as pitch, speaker embedding, and loudness, but also the residual information like speaking style, emotion, and prosody. The problem with this approach is that the model may rely solely on the latent space, ignoring the provided attributes altogether, which could reduce the interpretability and control over the speech generation process.

To address this issue, we propose a solution that introduces a dropout mechanism on the latent space. Specifically, during training, we randomly sample a probability and compare it to a fixeThe central question is: what does this latent space actually encode? Is it capturing complementary information that is not present in the attributes, or is there redundancy and potential conflict between the two representations?d threshold. If the sampled value is below the threshold, the latent space is deactivated (set to zero), forcing the model to rely solely on the explicit attributes—such as pitch, speaker embedding, and loudness—to generate the mel-spectrogram. Otherwise, the latent space is activated and combined with the attributes via cross-attention. This strategy prevents the model from depending exclusively on the latent space and encourages it to leverage the provided attributes, resulting in more interpretable and controllable speech generation.

(Algorithm) Forcing the use of attributes in AnCoGen using latent space dropout.

Input:
- Attributes \(A\): pitch, content, speaker embedding, loudness
- Latent space \(Z \in \mathbb{R}^{N \times d}\) (trainable vectors)
- Dropout threshold \(\tau \in [0,1]\)
- Mel-spectrogram \(x\)

Algorithm:

  1. Sample probability \(p \sim \mathcal{U}(0, 1)\)
  2. If \(p > \tau\):
      2.1 Use latent space \(Z\)
      2.2 Combine \(Z\) and \(x\) using cross-attention
       \(Z_{att}\) = \(\text{Attn}(Q=Z,\ K=x,\ V=x)\)
    Else:
      2.3 Replace \(Z \leftarrow \mathbf{\emptyset}\) (disable latent space)
      2.4 Use only attributes \(A\) and \(x\)
  3. \(\texttt{AnCoGen}(x,\ A, \ Z_{att})\)

Experiments

Set-up

In this work, we trained the AnCoGen model enhanced with a learnable latent space using the LibriSpeech 360 Clean dataset. The training data was preprocessed to extract four types of attributes: Pitch (using CREPE), Loudness using the root-mean-square energy (RMSE), Speaker identity embeddings obtained from a pretrained speaker encoder Content represented by phonetic posteriorgrams (PPGs) derived from a forced-alignment model. The model was trained using 4 NVIDIA A100 GPUs, with a batch size of 128 and the AdamW optimizer.

Architecture

The architecture used in this work builds upon the original AnCoGen model. Both the encoder and decoder consist of 6 Transformer layers, each comprising multi-head self-attention mechanisms, position-wise feedforward networks, and layer normalization. To enhance the model’s capacity to capture residual information, we introduce a latent space composed of 50 trainable vectors, each having the same dimensionality as the internal representations used in AnCoGen. These latent vectors interact with the input attributes (pitch, loudness, content, and speaker identity) via a cross-attention mechanism (see Section Section 2.1), enabling the model to infer and encode complementary information not explicitly present in the conditioning attributes.

Metrics:

To evaluate the quality and intelligibility of the generated speech, we rely on a combination of objective and perceptual metrics:

  • STOI ↑ (Short-Time Objective Intelligibility) (Taal et al. 2010): Measures the intelligibility of speech. Higher values indicate better intelligibility.
  • N-MOS ↑ (Neural Mean Opinion Score) (Kumar et al. 2023): A predicted MOS (Mean Opinion Score) estimated using a pretrained model such as SQUIM. It reflects the naturalness of speech on a 1–5 scale.
  • speechBertScore ↑ (Saeki et al. 2024): Computed by passing the generated speech through an ASR system. Higher score values indicate better intelligibility and linguistic accuracy.
  • COS ↑ (Cosine Similarity on speaker embeddings): Measures the similarity between speaker embeddings of the generated and reference speech, providing an estimate of speaker consistency.

Improving speech synthesis through latent space

Table 1 presents the synthesis quality obtained using AnCoGen, comparing two verisons of AnCoGen: with and without the additional latent space. The experiment involves analyzing a speech signal by extracting its attributes (analysis), and then reconstructing the audio signal from these attributes, either with or without the residual information captured in the latent space.

The results demonstrate a clear improvement in performance when the latent space is included. Specifically, STOI increased by +0.05, synthesis quality as measured by N-MOS improved by +0.28, content preservation assessed via SpeechBERTScore rose by +0.03, and speaker similarity saw a substantial gain of +0.09.

The central question is: what does this latent space actually encode? Is it capturing complementary information that is not present in the attributes, or is there redundancy and potential conflict between the two representations?

Uncovering the information encoded in the latent space

Since the AnCoGen model relies on Transformers to predict masked tokens, we can control the masking rate to selectively remove attributes and/or the additional latent space. This enables us to evaluate how the latent space contributes to the synthesis process, and to what extent it complements or compensates for missing attribute information. Table 2 summarizes the results of audio synthesis when attributes and/or the latent space are selectively removed.

This table clearly demonstrates that when audio synthesis is performed without the additional latent space (second row), the results closely align with those of the AnCoGen model trained without it (as shown in Table 1). This confirms that the model relies effectively on the attributes for synthesis. In contrast, the third row — where attributes are removed and only the latent space is used — shows a substantial drop in both content and quality, as expected. Nevertheless, the latent space still achieves a relatively high speaker similarity score, suggesting that it encodes meaningful identity information. Finally, the last row, which combines both attributes and the latent space during synthesis, leads to consistent improvements across all similarity metrics. This highlights the role of the latent space as a residual component that complements the attributes and further enhances synthesis quality.

How dropout (\(\tau\)) shapes information flow in the latent space

This section explores how varying the dropout threshol (\(\tau\)) influences the flow of information between the attributes and the residual latent space. To this end, we train several models with different dropout values \(\tau\), ranging from 0 (the latent space is always available during training) to 1 (the model relies solely on the attributes, with no access to the latent space).

In Figure 2, we observe that when \(\tau\) is equal to zero, the AnCoGen model relies almost entirely on the latent space for audio reconstruction, making minimal use of the attributs. As \(\tau\) increases (starting around 0.5), the model begins to effectively integrate both the attributes and the latent space, resulting in improved content preservation, speaker similarity, and overall synthesis quality. However, for higher values of \(\tau\) (above 0.8), the model tends to disregard the latent space and relies almost exclusively on the attributes for synthesis.

Encoding noise through an additional latent space

Previously, we showed that the latent space captures residual information not represented by the attributes, such as subtle content variations, accent, timbre, and breathing. In this section, we extend our approach to the semi-supervised encoding of noise within this space, treating noise as a form of residual speech information.
